WEBVTT

00:00.892 --> 00:02.214
[SPEAKER_43]: He's coming out.

00:04.136 --> 00:10.343
[SPEAKER_27]: Now is the moment for Britain to choose its future and we will have a general election on the 4th of July.

00:13.527 --> 00:18.133
[SPEAKER_31]: It's time to stop the chaos and rebuild our country together.

00:18.914 --> 00:23.119
[SPEAKER_27]: We Conservatives have got a clear plan to secure our future.

00:51.567 --> 00:57.112
[SPEAKER_39]: Good evening and welcome to Grimsby and welcome to Sky's Election Leaders event.

00:57.132 --> 01:20.815
[SPEAKER_39]: Right now you can see Rishi Sunak, the Prime Minister, the man who's hoping to get another term in office and to win the election, is leaving the car and entering Grimsby Town Hall, where of course he is going to face that grilling from our political editor, Beth Rigby, and then the live audience of viewers

01:21.807 --> 01:23.409
[SPEAKER_39]: And there he is, there is Rishi Sunak.

01:24.350 --> 01:27.374
[SPEAKER_39]: A few protesters outside the town hall here in Grimsby.

01:27.414 --> 01:34.964
[SPEAKER_39]: He's entering the room, ready to face the Sky News election leaders event.

01:35.344 --> 01:39.629
[SPEAKER_39]: Quick handshake with the Sky News chairman, David Rhodes.

01:39.649 --> 01:41.672
[SPEAKER_39]: And the Prime Minister is now in the building.

01:42.479 --> 01:48.432
[SPEAKER_39]: Two men, two policy platforms, two pitches to the public.

01:48.452 --> 01:51.519
[SPEAKER_39]: But in 22 days' time, only one will be entering No.

01:51.539 --> 01:53.864
[SPEAKER_39]: 10 Downing Street as Prime Minister.

01:54.325 --> 01:56.169
[SPEAKER_39]: This is a battle for No.

01:56.189 --> 01:56.590
[SPEAKER_39]: 10.

02:06.442 --> 02:10.165
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, hello, and welcome to the spin room here in Grimsby Town Hall.

02:10.205 --> 02:18.252
[SPEAKER_39]: There's now less than a half an hour to go until Keir Starmer will come onto the stage in the room that's just around the corner from where we are right now.

02:18.593 --> 02:23.337
[SPEAKER_39]: He'll then be followed by Rishi Sunak, who, of course, we saw entering the building just a few moments ago.

02:23.737 --> 02:31.123
[SPEAKER_39]: They will both face a 20-minute interview with our political editor, Beth Rigby, and then a 25-minute Q&A with an audience.

02:31.163 --> 02:36.448
[SPEAKER_39]: So if you haven't made up your mind about who to vote for, well, this is your perfect chance to see them

02:36.428 --> 02:36.869
[SPEAKER_39]: close.

02:37.611 --> 02:40.277
[SPEAKER_39]: The two men will be head-to-head in the most meaningful sense.

02:40.297 --> 02:45.669
[SPEAKER_39]: They'll be answering questions, they'll be explaining themselves and they'll be articulating their vision.

02:45.749 --> 02:48.455
[SPEAKER_39]: So if you want a direct comparison, this is it.

02:49.417 --> 02:52.885
[SPEAKER_39]: And there's one more thing that I want to say before we get cracking.

02:52.865 --> 02:56.774
[SPEAKER_39]: It's easy to think that this is an election campaign without much jeopardy.

02:57.396 --> 03:03.009
[SPEAKER_39]: A campaign where we already know the outcome, but there is an awful lot of jeopardy tonight.

03:03.149 --> 03:08.783
[SPEAKER_39]: For Rishi Sunak, it's one of his last chances to turn things around and to save his election campaign.

03:09.324 --> 03:10.587
[SPEAKER_39]: For Keir Starmer...

03:10.567 --> 03:12.030
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, frankly, it's his to lose.

03:12.110 --> 03:19.805
[SPEAKER_39]: If Labour's strategy has been to carefully carry that Ming vase across the floor, well, tonight, he's got to get through 45 minutes without breaking it.

03:20.026 --> 03:20.707
[SPEAKER_39]: Will he manage it?

03:21.208 --> 03:24.414
[SPEAKER_39]: And, of course, the big question, who will come out on top?

03:24.996 --> 03:32.811
[SPEAKER_39]: Both leaders have spent the day here in Grimsby and Cleethorpes, and just to warn you, there are some flashing images to come as well.

03:33.736 --> 03:37.703
[SPEAKER_39]: Mr Keir Starmer arrived here a short time ago after touring the sets.

03:38.064 --> 03:43.093
[SPEAKER_39]: The Labour leader said he's looking forward to tonight, and he talked about the work that he's done preparing.

03:43.154 --> 03:51.068
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, our Deputy Political Editor, Sam Coates, joins us now.

03:51.309 --> 03:53.232
[SPEAKER_39]: Sam, a huge moment for both men.

03:53.292 --> 03:54.715
[SPEAKER_39]: What are they going to be hoping for?

03:55.454 --> 04:00.582
[SPEAKER_25]: The question, Sophie, is will this define the election campaign?

04:01.002 --> 04:22.474
[SPEAKER_25]: Here we are at the halfway point, more or less, to July the 4th, and there's been a lot of frenetic activity over the first few weeks, but this is a moment with extended interviews and with questions from a key audience, an audience that really speaks for so much of the most important bits of the electorate that are going to the polls on

04:22.454 --> 04:24.680
[SPEAKER_25]: that will be visiting the polls on July the 4th.

04:24.941 --> 04:28.531
[SPEAKER_25]: The question is whether or not we get something new and something different.

04:28.671 --> 04:35.691
[SPEAKER_25]: This campaign has been marked by promises, promises that we've tried to scratch the surface of, but can we go deeper now?

04:36.453 --> 04:37.476
[SPEAKER_25]: Let's be absolute.

04:37.456 --> 04:45.883
[SPEAKER_25]: absolutely clear about the picture, the polling picture, as it were, that we're going into with this debate.

04:45.903 --> 04:53.270
[SPEAKER_25]: And if we just look at those polls as they go back, over months and months and months, Labour has been ahead.

04:54.050 --> 04:58.454
[SPEAKER_25]: It's been decisively ahead by about 20 percentage points.

04:58.935 --> 05:00.836
[SPEAKER_25]: And it has maintained that lead.

05:01.257 --> 05:07.362
[SPEAKER_25]: That is the reason why you're completely right to say it is Keir Starmer's to lose at the moment.

05:07.342 --> 05:12.329
[SPEAKER_25]: But he's such a new prospect as Prime Minister when it comes to the British public.

05:12.509 --> 05:13.330
[SPEAKER_25]: Do we know enough?

05:13.450 --> 05:14.532
[SPEAKER_25]: Can we find out some more?

05:14.632 --> 05:19.158
[SPEAKER_25]: How will he deal with spending and tax and borrowing beyond the soundbites that we've had?

05:19.519 --> 05:20.781
[SPEAKER_25]: That's the kind of challenge for him.

05:21.482 --> 05:27.230
[SPEAKER_25]: How can Rishi Sunak keep his party together in all the turmoil in the months to come if he's re-elected?

05:27.450 --> 05:31.155
[SPEAKER_25]: We'll find out more probably almost certainly after 7.30.

05:31.135 --> 05:33.941
[SPEAKER_39]: Yes, it's going to be so exciting, isn't it, Sam?

05:33.961 --> 05:37.849
[SPEAKER_39]: And I know that you're going to have some snap polling to bring us to that I'm really looking forward to.

05:38.070 --> 05:43.621
[SPEAKER_39]: Sam Coates there, with a build-up to what could be a decisive moment in the election campaign.

05:43.641 --> 05:46.748
[SPEAKER_39]: We're in the spin room now, just to give you a bit of context.

05:46.908 --> 05:50.856
[SPEAKER_39]: And really, the atmosphere has been building and building and building over the last few hours.

05:50.916 --> 05:51.658
[SPEAKER_39]: It's filling up.

05:51.638 --> 06:05.380
[SPEAKER_39]: We've got kind of TV reporters on one side, the newspaper journalist in the middle, and then politicians floating around already trying to, I guess, drop a few words in everyone's ear to try and be the chief cheerleaders for their man tonight.

06:05.421 --> 06:15.537
[SPEAKER_39]: But, of course, the big events, of course, kicking off at 7.30 with a forensic interview from Beth Rigby and then, of course, the audience Q&A as well.

06:16.529 --> 06:17.230
[SPEAKER_39]: Why are we here?

06:17.570 --> 06:19.453
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, it's worth talking about Grimsby for a moment, isn't it?

06:19.493 --> 06:25.260
[SPEAKER_39]: Because the new Great Grimsby and Cleethorpes constituency is a key battleground in this election.

06:25.421 --> 06:29.686
[SPEAKER_39]: The area turned Conservative for the first time since the Second World War in 2019.

06:29.927 --> 06:31.989
[SPEAKER_39]: That was, of course, under Boris Johnson.

06:32.470 --> 06:36.736
[SPEAKER_39]: And here on Sky News, we've been gauging the political mood here for the last six months.

06:36.756 --> 06:41.762
[SPEAKER_39]: I've been up a couple of times, many of my colleagues as well, to really get under the skin of the place.

06:41.802 --> 06:43.144
[SPEAKER_39]: Here's a little flavour.

06:45.048 --> 06:48.377
[SPEAKER_39]: Hello and welcome to a special edition of the Politics Hub.

06:48.818 --> 06:51.605
[SPEAKER_39]: We're here in the constituency of Great Grimsby and Cleethorpes.

06:51.685 --> 06:54.553
[SPEAKER_39]: A long way from the politics of Westminster.

06:54.753 --> 06:57.721
[SPEAKER_38]: It is going to be a fierce battleground in this election.

06:57.801 --> 07:01.892
[SPEAKER_38]: In 2019, the Conservatives took this area from Labour.

07:01.872 --> 07:04.996
[SPEAKER_38]: for the first time since World War II.

07:05.237 --> 07:07.500
[SPEAKER_17]: When Boris was here, he was like a film star.

07:07.900 --> 07:10.243
[SPEAKER_17]: I don't think the others will quite get the same reaction.

07:10.423 --> 07:12.687
[SPEAKER_33]: What are the big issues that matter to you right now?

07:12.947 --> 07:13.648
[SPEAKER_33]: Cost of living.

07:13.668 --> 07:15.450
[SPEAKER_33]: Bills forever going up and food going up.

07:15.891 --> 07:16.912
[SPEAKER_24]: The issue with the NHS.

07:17.112 --> 07:18.354
[SPEAKER_24]: People still can't afford to buy houses.

07:18.554 --> 07:20.497
[SPEAKER_24]: Invest in these towns up here more.

07:21.138 --> 07:23.401
[SPEAKER_51]: We're not picking up as a country, we're going back.

07:23.741 --> 07:26.605
[SPEAKER_20]: For me, it comes down to one word, hope.

07:26.625 --> 07:28.428
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, hope that, you know, things are going to change.

07:28.488 --> 07:30.951
[SPEAKER_39]: We're just trying to get a bit of a sense about what people think about politicians.

07:31.420 --> 07:34.706
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, I can't say what I want to say because it's on the telly.

07:34.786 --> 07:37.190
[SPEAKER_12]: But they're promising the world just to get you across.

07:38.031 --> 07:39.694
[SPEAKER_12]: And then when they get in, you don't get an out.

07:45.524 --> 07:48.368
[SPEAKER_39]: Well, our national correspondent Tom Parmenter is here in Grimsby tonight.

07:48.388 --> 07:49.190
[SPEAKER_39]: He joins us now.

07:49.230 --> 07:52.315
[SPEAKER_39]: Tom, that sense of disillusionment a real factor here in Grimsby?

07:53.881 --> 07:54.302
[SPEAKER_20]: It is.

07:54.362 --> 08:06.659
[SPEAKER_20]: And as you can see, we've spent an awful lot of time here this year trying to understand just what are the people's priorities in this election, in a corner of the country that feels that it has been overlooked for far too long.

08:06.700 --> 08:22.302
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, we've been to cobbler's shops, to care homes, to allotments, to Grimsby Town Football Club, to the housing estates, to try and understand just what matters to people and what is going right and what is going wrong in their lives at the moment and what they want their government to do about it.

08:22.282 --> 08:34.833
[SPEAKER_20]: That will be a big theme through the course of tonight as we get ready for this potentially really pivotal moment in this election campaign, in this new constituency.

08:35.394 --> 08:42.781
[SPEAKER_20]: And I've spent some time this afternoon with some of the audience members who have gathered in Grimsby tonight for this event.

08:43.341 --> 08:52.069
[SPEAKER_20]: And it is the people of this constituency that have made it happen by sharing their views so vividly over the last few months.

08:52.049 --> 09:00.703
[SPEAKER_20]: having spoken to a few of the audience members this afternoon, they are set and ready to go with some very tough questions for Rishi Sunak and Saqir Starmer.

09:00.723 --> 09:09.617
[SPEAKER_20]: And the one thing that I've really taken away from reporting from here throughout this year is that they are unvarnished political opinions that you get in Grimsby and Cleethorpes.

09:09.938 --> 09:13.143
[SPEAKER_20]: They've got no time for the spin, no time for the waffly answers.

09:13.403 --> 09:16.909
[SPEAKER_20]: They want direct honesty from the men on stage tonight.

09:18.948 --> 09:20.169
[SPEAKER_39]: absolutely right.

09:20.329 --> 09:23.032
[SPEAKER_39]: I love the way you put it, sharing their opinions so vividly.

09:23.452 --> 09:36.205
[SPEAKER_39]: The Prime Minister has had a bumpy start to the election campaign, but the big question tonight, can Rishi Sunak seize the opportunity to begin turning that around?

09:36.265 --> 09:44.333
[SPEAKER_39]: Joining us now from the Conservative Party is the exchequer secretary to the Treasury, Gareth Davis.

09:44.393 --> 09:46.035
[SPEAKER_39]: I guess the question is,

09:46.015 --> 09:53.547
[SPEAKER_39]: Is it all over for the Conservative Party, or can an event like tonight change the narrative of this election campaign?

09:53.567 --> 09:55.150
[SPEAKER_24]: It is absolutely not over.

09:55.210 --> 09:57.454
[SPEAKER_24]: We are in it to win it, fighting for every vote.

09:57.494 --> 10:01.761
[SPEAKER_24]: The only poll that matters, as you know very well, is on 4 July.

10:01.821 --> 10:09.694
[SPEAKER_24]: Events like tonight allow the Prime Minister to set out who he is, his values of aspiration and hard work that were instilled in him

10:09.674 --> 10:14.281
[SPEAKER_24]: from a young age, but it also allows him to set out the clear difference with Keir Starmer and the Labour Party.

10:14.782 --> 10:17.066
[SPEAKER_24]: Obviously, the biggest difference is on tax.

10:17.086 --> 10:19.470
[SPEAKER_24]: We're going to cut tax, we're going to cut national insurance contributions.

10:19.490 --> 10:20.611
[SPEAKER_39]: You're not going to cut tax.

10:20.752 --> 10:22.034
[SPEAKER_39]: I've just got to come in there.

10:22.755 --> 10:26.721
[SPEAKER_39]: Yes, you're going to reduce the amount that tax is going to go up by, but you're not planning on cutting tax.

10:26.701 --> 10:28.223
[SPEAKER_24]: So, let's deal with this really directly.

10:28.263 --> 10:30.987
[SPEAKER_24]: We are going to cut taxes on working people.

10:31.007 --> 10:33.371
[SPEAKER_24]: So, if you are in a job... That's not what you said, though, is it?

10:33.391 --> 10:35.113
[SPEAKER_24]: ..you pay national insurance contributions.

10:35.955 --> 10:38.859
[SPEAKER_24]: And we did that at the last part of the Parliament.

10:38.939 --> 10:45.809
[SPEAKER_24]: So, in six months, we cut national insurance contributions for 29 million people, saving about £900 for the average earner.

10:45.829 --> 10:56.505
[SPEAKER_24]: We want to go further, cut another 2% off national insurance for people in work, but we also want to abolish national insurance for the 4 million self-employed people, because they're the ones taking the risk in our economy.

10:56.485 --> 11:00.250
[SPEAKER_39]: You said at the beginning of the interview that it's not all over.

11:00.270 --> 11:01.111
[SPEAKER_39]: You're in it to win it.

11:01.572 --> 11:10.284
[SPEAKER_39]: If that is the case, then why is Grant Shapps, the Defence Secretary, going out on the broadcast airwave to say that, actually, it's all about making sure that Keir Starmer doesn't get a super majority?

11:10.625 --> 11:11.666
[SPEAKER_39]: That's not the script, is it?

11:11.946 --> 11:15.672
[SPEAKER_24]: What he's saying is, don't write a blank cheque for Keir Starmer.

11:15.712 --> 11:18.976
[SPEAKER_24]: Don't, you know, don't vote for something you don't know what he's going to do.

11:18.996 --> 11:22.481
[SPEAKER_39]: I mean, it doesn't sound like that's a party trying to win.

11:22.521 --> 11:25.345
[SPEAKER_39]: It sounds like that's a party trying not to lose really badly.

11:25.325 --> 11:29.093
[SPEAKER_24]: No, we are absolutely trying to win, believe me.

11:29.514 --> 11:38.693
[SPEAKER_24]: And I think the other thing that Grant was pointing out was that a vote for anybody other than the Conservative Party will allow Keir Starmer into 10 Downing Street.

11:38.713 --> 11:40.617
[SPEAKER_24]: And we know that that comes with

11:40.934 --> 11:45.540
[SPEAKER_24]: We know that income comes with lots of other things that are not going to be good for families across Britain.

11:45.620 --> 11:46.902
[SPEAKER_24]: So that's what he's saying.

11:47.042 --> 11:49.785
[SPEAKER_39]: And you think that tonight could be a game-changer then in the election, do you?

11:49.846 --> 12:07.228
[SPEAKER_24]: I think any opportunity that Rishi Sunak has to engage with the public, he does really well, because he is ultimately not just a nice guy, but he's somebody that is deeply driven by core values, and you can see that in the policies he's putting forward in a very detailed manifesto, and he will take the opportunity tonight to set that out.

12:07.208 --> 12:08.149
[SPEAKER_39]: looking forward to that.

12:08.169 --> 12:31.140
[SPEAKER_39]: Thank you very much indeed Gareth Davis there speaking to us as we build up to the main event because there's just over three weeks to go until the election and of course there is, just take a quick time check, just around 18 minutes to go until our main event here kicks off, the Leaders event here on Sky News where you will get the chance to directly compare

12:31.120 --> 12:33.164
[SPEAKER_39]: both Rishi Sunak and Sir Keir Starmer.

12:33.184 --> 12:42.080
[SPEAKER_39]: And that matters because although it might look like, according to the polls, that Keir Starmer's cruising to a comfortable win, there are always some tough tests on the road to Downing Street.

12:42.140 --> 12:44.385
[SPEAKER_39]: And one of them, of course, comes tonight.

12:44.465 --> 12:47.470
[SPEAKER_39]: We can talk now to the Shadow Health Secretary, Wes Streeting.

12:47.490 --> 12:49.554
[SPEAKER_39]: Good to have you here in Grimsby.

12:50.215 --> 12:52.740
[SPEAKER_39]: So, I mean, I guess it's Keir Starmer's to lose tonight, is it?

12:53.142 --> 12:59.310
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, the great thing about tonight's format is that as well as questions from Beth, we also get questions from the audience.

12:59.891 --> 13:02.314
[SPEAKER_21]: These are the sorts of interactions Keir really enjoys.

13:02.374 --> 13:05.018
[SPEAKER_21]: And it's a chance for us to do two things, I think.

13:05.598 --> 13:10.725
[SPEAKER_21]: One is to get across Labour's message of change and how we'll bring it about in terms of the policies.

13:11.346 --> 13:18.295
[SPEAKER_21]: And secondly, to make sure that people get the message that the only way this country gets the change we need is if people vote for it.

13:18.475 --> 13:20.398
[SPEAKER_21]: And I think it's been extraordinary

13:20.378 --> 13:23.301
[SPEAKER_21]: this morning to hear a senior cabinet minister.

13:23.669 --> 13:30.315
[SPEAKER_21]: effectively throwing the election, saying, oh, the Conservatives, oh, we've got to just try and stop this landslide Labour majority.

13:30.455 --> 13:44.689
[SPEAKER_21]: I mean, this is a deliberate calculation to try and persuade millions of people who are undecided, but in fact the whole country who haven't yet voted, that change is inevitable and therefore you don't have to go and vote for it.

13:44.849 --> 13:46.691
[SPEAKER_21]: And, you know, our message is simple.

13:46.871 --> 13:48.012
[SPEAKER_21]: The country needs change.

13:48.052 --> 13:51.415
[SPEAKER_21]: We will only get that change if people vote for change by voting Labour.

13:51.395 --> 13:55.941
[SPEAKER_39]: It is fair to say that the polls are pointing towards a Labour win right now.

13:56.702 --> 14:05.153
[SPEAKER_39]: It's on you, isn't it, to level with people and to be really, really honest about what the next five years will look like if you win the election.

14:05.193 --> 14:14.165
[SPEAKER_39]: And let's be honest, Labour talk about growth, they talk about planning reforms, but are you talking about the real difficult decisions that would face you if you are to win the election?

14:14.725 --> 14:16.828
[SPEAKER_39]: Public spending cuts, tax rises?

14:16.910 --> 14:19.935
[SPEAKER_21]: To be fair, we've been honest about those choices for some time.

14:20.056 --> 14:27.569
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm regularly inundated with people saying, I want you to promise X or Y, either on health or more broadly.

14:27.609 --> 14:31.796
[SPEAKER_21]: And I think when people see the manifesto tomorrow, they can take two things from it.

14:32.357 --> 14:38.007
[SPEAKER_21]: One is that every policy that's in there is a promise we can keep and the country can afford.

14:37.987 --> 14:53.228
[SPEAKER_21]: And secondly, there'll be things that they might have wanted us to do that won't be in there, because the state of the public finances is so appalling that there are good Labour things we'd have liked to do, but because we can't guarantee we'll deliver it in the first term of a Labour government, it's not made the manifesto.

14:53.309 --> 14:59.157
[SPEAKER_21]: And therein lies the difficult choices and the honesty with the public about the state of the finances.

14:59.197 --> 15:04.264
[SPEAKER_21]: And what a contrast with what we saw yesterday, which could see people's mortgages rising by £4,800.

15:04.244 --> 15:04.985
[SPEAKER_39]: Fifteen minutes to go.

15:05.005 --> 15:07.309
[SPEAKER_39]: I just want to squeeze in one final question to you.

15:07.530 --> 15:08.051
[SPEAKER_39]: Big event.

15:08.431 --> 15:09.213
[SPEAKER_39]: You know Keir Starmer.

15:09.233 --> 15:10.234
[SPEAKER_39]: How's he been preparing?

15:10.334 --> 15:11.917
[SPEAKER_39]: Give us any little nuggets, any detail?

15:12.158 --> 15:19.069
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, I saw him yesterday when Keir was trying to get me to brush my teeth in front of a class full of kids and then do star jumps in the playground.

15:19.130 --> 15:19.430
[SPEAKER_21]: Did you do it?

15:19.450 --> 15:20.151
[SPEAKER_21]: No, I bloody didn't.

15:20.231 --> 15:23.036
[SPEAKER_21]: I think it's fair to say Keir is enjoying himself on the campaign.

15:23.297 --> 15:25.240
[SPEAKER_21]: He's loving being out on the campaign trail.

15:25.220 --> 15:35.549
[SPEAKER_21]: he sees tonight as a great opportunity to show, I think, the wider country, who don't see him in person on the campaign trail, how much he enjoys interacting and answering the questions and setting out Labour's story.

15:35.569 --> 15:38.192
[SPEAKER_39]: We'll see if he does any star jumps after that interview with Beth Rupby.

15:38.232 --> 15:38.952
[SPEAKER_39]: Let's see how he gets on.

15:38.992 --> 15:40.013
[SPEAKER_39]: Wes, thank you very much indeed.

15:40.033 --> 15:42.616
[SPEAKER_39]: Wes Streeting, they're the Shadow Health Secretary.

15:42.656 --> 15:51.784
[SPEAKER_39]: We are just moments away now from a debate that could prove decisive in this election campaign, with Rishi Sunak and Keir Starmer preparing to go on stage.

15:52.124 --> 15:55.227
[SPEAKER_39]: Here's Sarah-Jay Mee with a little bit more on what we have in store for you.

15:55.207 --> 16:01.841
[SPEAKER_33]: The stage is set for the battle for number 10, live from here at Grimsby Town Hall.

16:01.861 --> 16:04.487
[SPEAKER_33]: We're in this wonderful main hall.

16:04.547 --> 16:06.431
[SPEAKER_33]: It's over 160 years old.

16:06.451 --> 16:14.970
[SPEAKER_33]: What a setting for the two leaders to put their case to you as to why they should be your next Prime Minister.

16:14.950 --> 16:21.917
[SPEAKER_33]: Well, these are the chairs that will be occupied by our political editor, Beth Rigby, and Sakir Starmer and Rishi Sunak.

16:22.118 --> 16:43.320
